eature of eighteenth-century newspapers. John warned neighbors against “entertaining her or harbouring her. . . or giving her credit.” Eunice defiantly replied, “If I am your wife, I am not your slave.” With this pointed but problematic analogy, Eunice connected her individual challenge to her husband’s authority with the broader critiques of patriarchal power found in the politics, religion, and literature of the British Atlantic world. Kirsten Sword’s richly researched history reconstructs the stories of wives who fled their husbands between the mid-seventeenth and early nineteenth centuries, comparing their plight with that of other runaway dependents. Wives not Slaves explores the links between local justice, the emerging press, and transatlantic political debates about marriage, slavery and imperial power. Sword traces the relationship between the distress of ordinary households, domestic unrest, and political unrest, shedding new light on the social changes imagined by eighteenth-century revolutionaries, and on the politics that determined which patriarchal forms and customs the new American nation would—and would not—abolish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEquality before the lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEqualityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMale domination (Social structure)zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarriage lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPatriarchyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSex discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSex rolezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Revolution.  aBritish Atlantic World.  aEnglish Civil Wars.  adivorce.  adomestic law.  amarriage.  anewspapers.  apatriarchal equilibrium.  arunaways.  aslavery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversit